<tr>
<td colspan="3" class="boilerplate metadata" style="line-height:10pt; padding:0.5em;"><small><b>Note</b>: This page may contain <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">IPA</a> phonetic symbols in <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>.</small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Tzotzil</b> (native name: <b>Bats'i k'op</b>; <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɓatsʼi kʼopʰ]</span>) is a <a href="/wiki/Mayan_languages" title="Mayan languages">Maya language</a> spoken by the <a href="/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_Mexico" title="Indigenous peoples of Mexico">indigenous</a> <a href="/wiki/Tzotzil_people" title="Tzotzil people">Tzotzil Maya people</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Mexican_state" title="Mexican state" class="mw-redirect">Mexican state</a> of <a href="/wiki/Chiapas" title="Chiapas">Chiapas</a>. According to an <a href="/wiki/INEGI" title="INEGI" class="mw-redirect">INEGI</a> (<i>Instituto Nacional de Estadística Geografía e Informática</i>) 2005 census, there are 329,937 speakers of Tzotzil in Mexico, making it the 6th most spoken indigenous language in the country. Most speakers are bilingual in <a href="/wiki/Spanish_language" title="Spanish language">Spanish</a> as a second language. In Central Chiapas, some primary schools and a secondary school are taught in Tzotzil.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Tzeltal" title="Tzeltal" class="mw-redirect">Tzeltal</a> is the most closely related language to Tzotzil and together they form a Tzeltalan sub-branch of the Mayan language family. Tzeltal, Tzotzil and <a href="/wiki/Ch%27ol_language" title="Ch'ol language">Ch'ol</a> are the most widely spoken languages in Chiapas.</p>
<p>There are six dialects of Tzotzil with varying degrees of mutual intelligibility, named after the different regions of Chiapas where they are spoken: <a href="/wiki/Chamula" title="Chamula">Chamula</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zinacant%C3%A1n" title="Zinacantán">Zinacantán</a>, <a href="/wiki/San_Andr%C3%A9s_Larr%C3%A1inzar" title="San Andrés Larráinzar">San Andrés Larráinzar</a>, <a href="/wiki/Huixt%C3%A1n" title="Huixtán">Huixtán</a>, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Ch%27enalho%27&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Ch'enalho' (page does not exist)">Ch'enalho'</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Venustiano_Carranza" title="Venustiano Carranza">Venustiano Carranza</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><i>Centro de Lengua, Arte y Literatura Indígena</i> (CELALI) suggested in 2002 that the name of the language (and the ethnicity) should be spelled Tsotsil, rather than Tzotzil. Native speakers and writers of the language are picking up the habit of using <i>s</i> instead of <i>z</i>.<sup class="Template-Fact" title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from February 2007" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</sup></p>
